<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15109</anchor> <rss>jms-00CK.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CK</addr>  <route>jms-00CK.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>-algebra equipped with an endomap <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ x }}{ X } \in \mathcal {C}</tex>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>x \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex> along <tex>x</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   <p>Suppose that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> is a homomorphism; we must check that the same map tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>.</p>  <ol>    <li>      First, we unfold the definition of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link>.
            <center><img src="resources/3c2f2712414db54cb70b8dfb8c9fdcd4-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Next, we use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/84826047201d2b0542fffb0c3c43221a-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We unfold the restricted algebra map.
            <center><img src="resources/6fd674e45880fd9a57338e746584b484-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we use the associativity law for the algebra <tex>X</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/1109af5d294db7d43e9bd8e2524f3954-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> again.
            <center><img src="resources/8b478ec8b749c7ac30f22997fbc20881-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We recall that <tex>\pi _{ I }</tex> and <tex>\alpha _{ I }</tex> are inverse.
            <center><img src="resources/ebe1b9137fba47c70a6dbb299d8ae577-web.svg"/></center>      </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15110</anchor> <rss>jms-00CF.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CF</addr>  <route>jms-00CF.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced monad algebra on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>15111</anchor> <rss>jms-00CD.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CD</addr>  <route>jms-00CD.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> that is a fixed point, i.e. the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. We may define the <em>induced <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>-algebra</em> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> to have the same carrier object as <tex>X</tex>  and with the algebra map <tex>{ T X } \xrightarrow {{ \alpha _{ \bar { X } } }}{ X }</tex> defined as follows:
        <center><img src="resources/b5b7acde271f540f1d2dba47feeb451a-web.svg"/></center>  </p></mainmatter> </tree><p>We must show that our <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">construction</link> in fact gives rise to a monad algebra.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>15112</anchor> <rss>jms-00CE.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CE</addr>  <route>jms-00CE.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Unitality of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">unital</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   <p>We are trying to check that the following morphism is an identity:</p>        <center><img src="resources/b9ce33d699bc8357511b499a4d319f05-web.svg"/></center>    <ol>    <li>We unfold the definition of the algebra map <tex>\alpha _{ \bar { X } }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/d281ab43f9049d15d34bd7f7c4d4f061-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We use the unit law for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/d6c14ab16cdf3778f9ebab1ca1b0cf1d-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Finally, we use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> is inverse to <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/da3ee3b8f07ac76e321dc22a78ad91fa-web.svg"/></center>      </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>15113</anchor> <rss>jms-00CG.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CG</addr>  <route>jms-00CG.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Associativity of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">associative</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   <p>We are trying to check that the following identity holds:</p>        <center><img src="resources/2b49455a9e41e08a01f4b6bfa5201a6a-web.svg"/></center>    <ol>    <li>      We will start on the right-hand side. We first unfold the definition of the algebra map.
    
            <center><img src="resources/3b99e294f91c4ac7d818518b104ffbb3-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> inverts <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/add10f7e0617793503a0b65ee9dd3663-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We use the associativity of the monad <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/9d5fb7b123d1002a68d3e7622f23cdb7-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Folding the definition of the algebra map, we have the desired cell.
            <center><img src="resources/b50b21835a0c4b19e6f52553853e6547-web.svg"/></center>      </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>15114</anchor> <rss>jms-00CH.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-00CH</addr>  <route>jms-00CH.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> is a monad algebra</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is in fact a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   Because it is <link href="jms-00CE.xml" type="local" title="Unitality of the induced monad algebra">unital</link> and <link href="jms-00CG.xml" type="local" title="Associativity of the induced monad algebra">associative</link>.
</block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>5</crumb></trail> <anchor>15115</anchor> <rss>jms-00CK.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CK</addr>  <route>jms-00CK.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>-algebra equipped with an endomap <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ x }}{ X } \in \mathcal {C}</tex>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>x \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex> along <tex>x</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   <p>Suppose that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> is a homomorphism; we must check that the same map tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>.</p>  <ol>    <li>      First, we unfold the definition of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link>.
            <center><img src="resources/3c2f2712414db54cb70b8dfb8c9fdcd4-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Next, we use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/84826047201d2b0542fffb0c3c43221a-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We unfold the restricted algebra map.
            <center><img src="resources/6fd674e45880fd9a57338e746584b484-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we use the associativity law for the algebra <tex>X</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/1109af5d294db7d43e9bd8e2524f3954-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> again.
            <center><img src="resources/8b478ec8b749c7ac30f22997fbc20881-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      We recall that <tex>\pi _{ I }</tex> and <tex>\alpha _{ I }</tex> are inverse.
            <center><img src="resources/ebe1b9137fba47c70a6dbb299d8ae577-web.svg"/></center>      </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15116</anchor> <rss>jms-00CQ.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CQ</addr>  <route>jms-00CQ.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">an algebra</link> for an endofunctor <tex>{ \mathcal {C} } \xrightarrow {{ F }}{ \mathcal {C} }</tex>, and let <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ x }}{ X }</tex> be an endomorphism in <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>. We define the <em>restriction</em> of <tex>X</tex> by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ x }}{ X }</tex> to be the <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> <tex>x \cdot   X</tex> whose carrier is <tex>X</tex> with <tex>{ F X } \xrightarrow {{ \alpha _{ x \cdot X } }}{ X }</tex> defined to be the following composite:</p>      <center><img src="resources/691d066900f22b157e51bdc10e5bc453-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15117</anchor> <rss>jms-00C7.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C7</addr>  <route>jms-00C7.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Homomorphism of algebras</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>F</tex> be an endofunctor on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>X , Y</tex> be a pair of <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebras for <tex>F</tex></link>; a <em>homomorphism</em> of algebras from <tex>X</tex> to <tex>Y</tex> is given by a morphism <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ h }}{ Y }</tex> in <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> that preserves the algebra structure in the following sense:</p>      <center><img src="resources/a100d2fb1bb3c7a0c6ea8fd4e6c70d71-web.svg"/></center>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15118</anchor> <rss>jms-00CD.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CD</addr>  <route>jms-00CD.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> that is a fixed point, i.e. the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. We may define the <em>induced <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>-algebra</em> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> to have the same carrier object as <tex>X</tex>  and with the algebra map <tex>{ T X } \xrightarrow {{ \alpha _{ \bar { X } } }}{ X }</tex> defined as follows:
        <center><img src="resources/b5b7acde271f540f1d2dba47feeb451a-web.svg"/></center>  </p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15119</anchor> <rss>jms-00C8.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C8</addr>  <route>jms-00C8.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Weak algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We shall refer to an <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> for the underlying endofunctor of a monad as a <em>weak algebra</em>, following <link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">Joyal and Moerdijk</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15120</anchor> <rss>jms-00CR.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CR</addr>  <route>jms-00CR.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>s \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline>   We have <link href="jms-00CK.xml" type="local" title="Lifting homomorphisms to the induced monad algebra">already seen</link> that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> tracks an <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>. It remains to show that this homomorphism preserves the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">successor operation</link>.
  <ol>    <li>      We first unfold the successor operation of the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> on <tex>I</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/d5edc41ec718645e12b1826e39fe92ec-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we use the algebra property of <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/59f3aa943874cb25d36d02053a50e7c9-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Then we unfold the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">restricted algebra structure</link>.
            <center><img src="resources/46e6731c1bd42216bc96a1d3231be24c-web.svg"/></center>      </li>    <li>      Finally we the unitality of the <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>X</tex>.
            <center><img src="resources/b0cd0b78bfb23cf347f6cd7bef104cdc-web.svg"/></center>      </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15121</anchor> <rss>joyal-moerdijk-1995.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>joyal-moerdijk-1995</addr>  <route>joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml</route> <date><year>1995</year>  </date> <authors><author><link href="andréjoyal.xml" type="local">André Joyal</link></author><author><link href="iekemoerdijk.xml" type="local">Ieke Moerdijk</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebraic set theory</title> <meta name="venue">Cambridge University Press</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree></references></backmatter></tree>